{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a45eebf27457201d", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== 2603.14877 ===\n# SoulX-Duplug: Plug-and-Play Streaming State Prediction Module for Realtime Full-Duplex Speech Conversation\narXiv: 2603.14877\nAuthors: Ruiqi Yan, Wenxi Chen, Zhanxun Liu, Ziyang Ma, Haopeng Lin, Hanlin Wen, Hanke Xie, Jun Wu, Yuzhe Liang, Yuxiang Zhao, Pengchao Feng, Jiale Qian, Hao Meng, Yuhang Dai, Shunshun Yin, Ming Tao, Lei Xie, Kai Yu, Xinsheng Wang, Xie Chen\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: dialogue_system\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose SoulX-Duplug, a bilingual streaming state prediction module that unifies VAD, ASR, and turn detection within a single framework to enable low-latency and semantically informed dialogue state control for modular full-duplex spoken dialogue systems.\n  2. We release SoulX-Duplug-Eval, a complementary benchmark that extends the Easy Turn testset and Full-Duplex-Bench, promoting more standardized and comparable cross-lingual assessment in future research.\n  3. SoulX-Duplug achieves streaming turn detection with an average latency of 240\\,ms, and a full-duplex spoken dialogue system built upon it outperforms existing systems across multiple evaluation settings, validating its downstream practicality.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/对话型, ASR, ASR/隐式对齐-AED\n=== 2604.12928 ===\n# MoshiRAG: Asynchronous Knowledge Retrieval for Full-Duplex Speech Language Models\narXiv: 2604.12928\nAuthors: Chung-Ming Chien, Manu Orsini, Eugene Kharitonov, Neil Zeghidour, Karen Livescu, Alexandre Défossez\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_agent\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes MoshiRAG, the first full-duplex speech language model equipped with retrieval-augmented generation to improve factuality without sacrificing real-time interactivity.\n  2. Introduces an asynchronous framework that exploits the natural temporal gap between response onset and core information delivery to seamlessly integrate external knowledge during conversation.\n  3. Develops a specialized training methodology with synthetic data that teaches the model to predict a retrieval trigger token and generate conversational filler while the back end fetches information.\n  4. Demonstrates that MoshiRAG achieves factuality comparable to the best turn-based speech language models while maintaining the low latency and full-duplex interactivity of the base Moshi model.\n  5. Shows that the modular design enables plug-and-play replacement of retrieval back ends at inference time, allowing performance improvements without retraining.\n  6. Validates strong out-of-domain generalization by successfully applying the retrieval mechanism as a tool to solve unseen mathematical reasoning tasks.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/对话型, Agent, Agent/Action\n=== 2508.07375 ===\n# TurnGuide: Enhancing Meaningful Full Duplex Spoken Interactions via Dynamic Turn-Level Text-Speech Interleaving\narXiv: 2508.07375\nAuthors: Wenqian Cui, Lei Zhu, Xiaohui Li, Zhihan Guo, Haoli Bai, Lu Hou, Irwin King\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: dialogue_system\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose TurnGuide, a novel text-speech interleaved generation approach for end-to-end full-duplex speech language models grounded in natural speech data.\n  2. We introduce a dynamic turn segmentation framework to address the insertion timing and length challenges of integrating text into double-channel dialogues.\n  3. We introduce a text-guided dialogue modeling framework that interleaves text and speech generation at the turn level to preserve natural acoustic flow.\n  4. We demonstrate through extensive experiments that TurnGuide significantly improves the semantic coherence of generated speech and achieves state-of-the-art performance on turn-taking events.\n\nTags: LALM/对话型-交错标记, LALM/对话型-纯语音, Agent/全双工\n=== 2602.13891 ===\n# GSRM: Generative Speech Reward Model for Speech RLHF\narXiv: 2602.13891\nAuthors: Maohao Shen, Tejas Jayashankar, Osama Hanna, Naoyuki Kanda, Yancheng Wang, Kateřina Žmolíková, Ruiming Xie, Niko Moritz, Anfeng Xu, Yashesh Gaur, Gregory Wornell, Qing He, Jilong Wu\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_other\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Curation of a large-scale human feedback dataset for speech naturalness, comprising 31k expert ratings on conversational TTS and an out-of-domain benchmark of real-world user-assistant speech interactions.\n  2. Introduction of a Generative Speech Reward Model (GSRM) that decomposes speech naturalness evaluation into interpretable acoustic feature extraction followed by feature-grounded chain-of-thought reasoning.\n  3. Development of a scalable CoT synthesis pipeline that generates high-quality reasoning trajectories by grounding textual logic in explicitly extracted paralinguistic acoustic cues.\n  4. Demonstration that GSRM substantially outperforms existing speech naturalness predictors, achieving model-human correlation that approaches human inter-rater consistency.\n  5. First application of an online RLHF framework to improve the naturalness of a full-duplex speech LLM by leveraging GSRM as a reward verifier.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/后训练-GRPO, Eval, Eval/听觉感知\n=== 2512.20156 ===\n# Fun-Audio-Chat Technical Report\narXiv: 2512.20156\nAuthors: Tongyi Fun Team, Qian Chen, Luyao Cheng, Chong Deng, Xiangang Li, Jiaqing Liu, Chao-Hong Tan, Wen Wang, Junhao Xu, Jieping Ye, Qinglin Zhang, Qiquan Zhang, Jingren Zhou\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Large-scale post-training and model scaling of the Dual-Resolution Speech Representations architecture and Core-Cocktail Training strategy to millions of hours of audio data and 8B/30B-A3B parameter scales while retaining a 50% reduction in training GPU hours.\n  2. Multi-Task DPO Training to enhance robustness, audio understanding, speech instruction-following, and voice empathy capabilities beyond basic supervised fine-tuning.\n  3. Comprehensive evaluation demonstrating top performance among similarly-scaled models on Spoken Question Answering and competitive results on audio understanding, speech function calling, speech instruction-following, and voice empathy benchmarks.\n  4. Extension of the model to a full-duplex variant, Fun-Audio-Chat-Duplex, which achieves strong performance on spoken question answering and full-duplex interaction metrics.\n  5. Open-sourcing of the Fun-Audio-Chat-8B model checkpoint, training and inference code, and an interactive demo.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/对话型, LALM/后训练-DPO\n=== 2509.21749 ===\n# Thinking with Sound: Audio Chain-of-Thought Enables Multimodal Reasoning in Large Audio-Language Models\narXiv: 2509.21749\nAuthors: Zhen Xiong, Yujun Cai, Zhecheng Li, Junsong Yuan, Yiwei Wang\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose Thinking-with-Sound (TwS), a novel reasoning framework that enables Large Audio-Language Models to perform audio chain-of-thought by interleaving linguistic reasoning with on-the-fly acoustic analysis.\n  2. We design MELD-Hard1k, a robustness-oriented benchmark that introduces various acoustic perturbations to systematically evaluate LALMs under challenging audio conditions.\n  3. We demonstrate through extensive experiments that TwS consistently improves LALMs' accuracy, robustness, and scalability across model sizes without requiring retraining.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/理解型, Agent, Agent/Planning, Agent/Action\n=== 2010.15258 ===\n# DNSMOS: A Non-Intrusive Perceptual Objective Speech Quality metric to evaluate Noise Suppressors\narXiv: 2010.15258\nAuthors: Chandan K A Reddy, Vishak Gopal, Ross Cutler\nYear: 2020 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_other\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of DNSMOS, a non-intrusive perceptual objective speech quality metric designed to evaluate noise suppressors without requiring a clean reference signal.\n  2. Development of a multi-stage self-teaching framework that effectively trains the prediction model using noisy human subjective ratings.\n  3. Demonstration that the proposed DNSMOS metric correlates significantly better with human ratings than widely used intrusive metrics like PESQ, POLQA, and SDR.\n  4. Empirical validation that the multi-stage self-teaching approach substantially improves the model's generalization to unseen speech categories such as non-English languages, emotional speech, and singing.\n\nTags: Eval, Eval/学习, Eval/听觉感知\n=== 2107.03312 ===\n# SoundStream: An End-to-End Neural Audio Codec\narXiv: 2107.03312\nAuthors: Neil Zeghidour, Alejandro Luebs, Ahmed Omran, Jan Skoglund, Marco Tagliasacchi\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose SoundStream, a neural audio codec in which all constituent components are trained end-to-end with a mix of reconstruction and adversarial losses to achieve superior audio quality.\n  2. We introduce a new residual vector quantizer and a novel quantizer dropout technique that enables a single model to handle different bitrates.\n  3. We demonstrate that learning the encoder brings a very significant coding efficiency improvement compared to using fixed mel-spectrogram features.\n  4. We demonstrate through subjective quality metrics that SoundStream outperforms both Opus and EVS over a wide range of bitrates.\n  5. We design our model to support streamable inference, which operates at low latency and runs in real-time on a smartphone CPU.\n  6. We propose a variant of the SoundStream codec that jointly performs audio compression and enhancement without introducing additional latency.\n\nTags: 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-声学", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "8553d6b6-3b21-4b05-a041-7caa414f31ff", "uuid": "407caa5a-4e41-462c-b764-02921ea5875f", "timestamp": "2026-07-06T13:02:41.285Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== 2603.14877 ===\n# SoulX-Duplug: Plug-and-Pla